# Risk Digital Twin Ontology

## Vision

The Risk Digital Twin is an AI-assisted semantic integration platform that continuously transforms heterogeneous internal and external information into a unified enterprise risk picture.

Unlike traditional risk registers, the platform does not start from risks.

It starts from information.

Information is collected from multiple sources, semantically interpreted using AI, transformed into common ontology objects, and connected to enterprise risks through risk factors.

The same architecture can later support Quality, Sustainability, Supply Chain, Commissioning and other Digital Twins.

---

# Main Principles

1. Business concepts are separated from technical integration.
2. Enterprise risks are independent of information sources.
3. One information source may support many risk factors.
4. One risk factor may influence many enterprise risks.
5. AI assists configuration but does not replace human approval.
6. Original information is always preserved.
7. Every decision is traceable back to its evidence.

---

# Core Architecture

Enterprise Risk
        ↓
Risk Definition
        ↓
Risk Factor
        ↓
Monitoring Capability
        ↓
Information Source
        ↓
Connector Definition
        ↓
Connector Instance
        ↓
Connector Runtime
        ↓
Raw Record
        ↓
AI Interpretation
        ↓
Knowledge Objects
        ↓
Risk Intelligence
        ↓
Dashboards / Alerts / Recommendations

---

# Core Objects

| Object | Purpose | Created by | Demo |
|---------|----------|------------|------|
| EnterpriseRiskCategory | Top-level enterprise taxonomy (Strategic, Financial, Supply Chain, Engineering, HSE, Cyber...) | Administrator | ✓ |
| RiskSubcategory | Second-level enterprise taxonomy | Administrator | ✓ |
| RiskDefinition | Generic reusable enterprise risk (Late Delivery, Supplier Insolvency, OT Attack...) | Administrator | ✓ |
| RiskFactor | Business factor influencing one or more enterprise risks (Weather, Commodity Prices, Politics, Labour Market, Supplier Capacity...) | Administrator / AI | ✓ |
| MonitoringCapability | Business definition describing WHAT should be monitored | User | ✓ |
| InformationSource (DataSource) | System or provider delivering information (SAP, FMI, Reuters, MEPS, Manual Expert...) | User | ✓ |
| ConnectorDefinition | Generic AI-generated connector template | AI + User | ✓ |
| ConnectorInstance | Configured execution of one connector | User | ✓ |
| ConnectorRun | One execution of ConnectorInstance | Runtime | Later |
| RawRecord | Original imported record | Runtime | ✓ |
| Interpretation | AI understanding of RawRecord | AI | ✓ |
| MappingSuggestion | AI proposal for ontology objects | AI | ✓ |
| KnowledgeObject | Common parent for semantic objects | System | ✓ |
| Entity | Supplier, Ship, Project, Material, Port, Country... | AI/User | ✓ |
| Observation | Current fact | AI/User | ✓ |
| Incident | Historical event | AI/User | ✓ |
| Evidence | Supporting information | AI/User | ✓ |
| RiskInstance | Actual risk affecting one or more entities | AI/User | ✓ |
| Relationship | Semantic relationship between objects | AI/User | ✓ |
| Mitigation | Risk response | User | Later |
| Recommendation | AI recommendation | AI | Later |
| Scenario | What-if simulation | User | Later |

---

# Risk Factors

Risk Factors are business concepts.

They are NOT information sources.

Examples:

- Weather
- Commodity Prices
- Inflation
- Interest Rates
- Politics & Conflicts
- Supplier Capacity
- Material Availability
- Labour Market
- Cyber Threats
- Environmental Regulation
- Pandemic
- Port Congestion

One Risk Factor may influence multiple enterprise risks.

One enterprise risk may depend on multiple risk factors.

---

# Monitoring Capability

Monitoring Capability describes WHAT the organisation wants to monitor.

Examples:

- Weather Monitoring
- Commodity Monitoring
- Supplier Monitoring
- Political Monitoring
- Cyber Monitoring
- Regulatory Monitoring

Monitoring Capability is independent from specific data providers.

---

# Information Sources

Information Sources provide evidence.

Examples:

Weather

- FMI
- OpenWeather
- ECMWF
- NOAA

Commodity Prices

- MEPS
- London Metal Exchange
- Trading Economics

Politics

- Reuters
- BBC
- Government Bulletins
- EU News

Supplier Information

- ERP
- Supplier Portal
- Manual Expert
- Historical Incidents

One Monitoring Capability may use multiple Information Sources.

One Information Source may support multiple Monitoring Capabilities.

---

# Connector Definition

Connector Definition is generated with AI.

Input:

- API documentation
- Swagger/OpenAPI
- Sample JSON
- CSV
- Excel
- XML
- Database schema
- PDF
- User description

AI suggests:

- transport
- authentication
- ingestion strategy
- parser
- polling frequency
- listening/webhook capability
- incremental loading
- field mapping
- semantic mapping
- confidence

User reviews and approves.

---

# Connector Instance

Connector Instance configures one execution.

Example

SAP Purchase Orders

↓

Production

↓

Test

↓

Project A

Each instance has:

- endpoint
- credentials
- schedule
- filters
- status
- last execution

---

# Raw Record

Raw Record is immutable.

It always preserves original information.

Nothing is lost.

---

# AI Interpretation

AI analyses Raw Records.

It identifies:

- entities
- observations
- incidents
- possible risk factors
- confidence
- explanation

No business object is automatically created.

---

# Mapping Suggestion

AI proposes

Create:

- Observation
- Incident
- Evidence
- Entity

Link to:

- Risk Definition
- Risk Factors
- Existing Entity

User can approve, modify or reject.

---

# Knowledge Objects

All semantic objects inherit common properties.

Examples:

Entity

Observation

Incident

Evidence

RiskInstance

Relationship

Common fields:

- id
- objectType
- source
- confidence
- createdAt
- updatedAt
- relationships[]

---

# Relationships

Relationships are first-class ontology objects.

Examples

Supplier

SUPPLIES

Project

Weather

AFFECTS

Sea Trial

Politics

CAUSES

Supplier Delay

Observation

SUPPORTS

Risk Instance

Evidence

PROVES

Observation

---

